d, Suffolk, England":"Bedingfield, Suffolk, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bedingfield","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Suffolk and Norfolk): variant of   Beddingfield  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Beddingfield","meanings":["English (Suffolk): habitational name from Bedingfield in Suffolk. The placename is recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Bedingefelda</i>, from the Old English personal name <i>Bēda</i> + the connective particle <i>-ing-</i> ‘associated with, named after’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country’."]}]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":7,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":16,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Peter de Bedingfield was born on 13 February 1320, in Bedingfield, Suffolk, England, his father, Sir Edmund Bedingfield, was 28 and his mother, Maude Hemenhale, was 24. He married Margaret Bacon about 1345, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. He died on 12 December 1372, in his hometown, at the age of 52, and was buried in Bedingfield, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"13 February 1320–12 December 1372":"13. veebruar 1320–12. detsember 1372","1320–1372":"1320–1372","1322–Male":"1322–Surnud","1324–1380":"1324–1380","1346–Female":"1346–Surnud","1348–1380":"1348–1380","1349–1435":"1349–1435","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1352–Female":"1352–Surnud","1292–Male":"1292–Surnud","1296–1329":"1296–1329","December 1372":"detsember 1372","12 December 1372":"12. detsember 1372","1352":"1352","1296":"1296","1350":"1350","1372":"1372","1292":"1292","1380":"1380","1349":"1349","1348":"1348","1337":"1337","1435":"1435","1346":"1346","1324":"1324","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","about 1345":"umbes 1345","13 February 1320":"13. veebruar 1320","1319":"1319","1329":"1329",